WEBVTT

00:03.760 --> 00:06.880
I'll be in London one week,
at this address.

00:07.160 --> 00:09.440
Finish your business here
and join me.

00:12.600 --> 00:14.080
TOMMY: <i>"Dear Grace...</i>

00:16.040 --> 00:19.720
<i>"Before the war, when I had
an important decision to make,</i>

00:20.400 --> 00:22.000
<i>"I used to flip a coin.</i>

00:23.200 --> 00:25.480
<i>"Perhaps that is what
I will do again."</i>

02:48.720 --> 02:51.280
...and give him peace. Amen.

02:52.120 --> 02:53.680
ALL: Amen.

02:59.880 --> 03:01.040
(CLEARS THROAT)

03:03.800 --> 03:06.160
I promised my friend
Freddie Thorne

03:07.560 --> 03:09.640
that I'd say a few words
over his grave

03:09.720 --> 03:11.400
if he should pass before me.

03:13.680 --> 03:17.600
I made this promise before
he became me brother-in-law.

03:18.360 --> 03:21.680
When we were in France,
fighting for the King.

03:21.760 --> 03:22.880
Amen.

03:25.040 --> 03:28.240
TOMMY: And in the end it
wasn't war that took Freddie.

03:28.320 --> 03:31.000
-(BABY CRYING)
-Pestilence took him.

03:31.440 --> 03:33.440
Come here.
(SHUSHING)

03:33.640 --> 03:38.280
But Freddie passed on his soul
and his spirit to a new generation

03:38.480 --> 03:41.120
-before he was cruelly taken.
-(BABY CONTINUOUS CRYING)

03:44.640 --> 03:46.560
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

03:49.040 --> 03:51.000
We thought, now Freddie's gone,

03:51.520 --> 03:54.120
-you might come back to Birmingham.
-(CHUCKLES)

03:56.560 --> 03:57.960
God, do you know how funny it is

03:58.040 --> 04:00.560
that you've got
chauffeurs in uniform now?

04:00.880 --> 04:02.880
It's just for the occasion, Ada.

04:03.320 --> 04:05.000
Do you know how unfair it is

04:05.080 --> 04:08.200
that you've got four Bugattis
when half the country's starving?

04:09.360 --> 04:12.600
So now they've made you ashamed
of us, eh? (CLEARS THROAT)

04:13.640 --> 04:16.880
Sometimes when I think how I used
to be, it makes me embarrassed.

04:16.960 --> 04:18.440
Karl's with his cousins.

04:18.720 --> 04:21.320
I caught 'em trying
to pinch flowers off a grave.

04:23.600 --> 04:24.680
Ada.

04:25.440 --> 04:26.960
Are you coming home?

04:27.280 --> 04:28.640
I'm going home.

04:29.760 --> 04:32.520
It's all right, Poll.
We make Ada embarrassed.

04:32.600 --> 04:34.280
That's not what I said.

04:36.720 --> 04:38.720
There's another reason
we want you home.

04:39.360 --> 04:41.200
We're planning an expansion.

04:41.280 --> 04:43.200
-I'm taking premises in London...
-(SIGHS)

04:43.280 --> 04:45.280
Tommy, it's a funeral,
business can wait.

04:45.360 --> 04:48.720
Polly, if Ada was
weeping then I'd stop.

04:48.800 --> 04:50.160
But she's not.

04:50.320 --> 04:52.480
The expansion means
it's going to be dangerous

04:52.560 --> 04:54.320
to be a Shelby in London
for a while.

04:54.880 --> 04:55.880
Yeah.

04:56.160 --> 04:58.320
Well, I'm not a Shelby any more.

05:00.280 --> 05:02.360
And I'm not a Thorne now, either.

05:04.240 --> 05:05.440
I'm free.

05:09.080 --> 05:10.800
I've got to get Karl home.

05:17.840 --> 05:19.800
-(SIGHS)
-I told you.

05:20.400 --> 05:21.720
Let me do it.

05:22.040 --> 05:23.360
It's all right.

05:23.640 --> 05:26.600
I'll have some men watch her house
till the danger passes.

05:33.000 --> 05:34.960
POLLY: "Till the danger passes"?

05:37.640 --> 05:39.160
That'll be the bloody day.

05:48.560 --> 05:50.600
(CHILDREN SHOUTING)

05:50.680 --> 05:52.080
Go on, move away, go on.

06:15.600 --> 06:18.320
It happened at, uh, exactly 7 a.m.

06:18.680 --> 06:22.360
Nobody saw anything.
Our patrols were not in the area.

06:24.680 --> 06:27.960
Mr Shelby, have you got
any idea who might've done it?

06:30.680 --> 06:33.800
I'd say it was something to do
with the gas. (CLEARS THROAT)

06:35.160 --> 06:36.840
It's just been fitted.

06:39.840 --> 06:42.360
Er, madam, the structure's
not yet declared safe.

06:42.640 --> 06:45.360
-(DEBRIS CRUNCHES)
-Madam!

06:56.120 --> 06:57.960
This is all over the place.

07:02.800 --> 07:04.040
Confetti.

07:08.600 --> 07:09.840
You can go.

07:10.080 --> 07:11.120
Right.

07:17.160 --> 07:18.320
Who?

07:21.720 --> 07:23.280
Who did this to us?

07:42.000 --> 07:44.240
Whiskey. Irish.

07:44.320 --> 07:45.600
(CLEARS THROAT)

07:58.880 --> 08:01.160
I heard there was a bit of a bang
in your part of town.

08:02.320 --> 08:04.240
Gas and electric don't mix.

08:04.680 --> 08:06.360
Who'd have thought
they would, eh?

08:06.680 --> 08:08.920
How's business otherwise,
Mr Shelby?

08:11.160 --> 08:12.600
You know something?

08:13.400 --> 08:15.400
In these times of hunger
and hardship,

08:15.480 --> 08:17.360
business is surprisingly good.

08:21.000 --> 08:23.480
Which one of you is
the Peaky Blinder devil?

08:30.720 --> 08:32.080
Gentlemen.

09:27.360 --> 09:29.440
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

09:32.000 --> 09:34.440
(INDISTINCT TALKING)

09:41.080 --> 09:42.800
Finn! Get in here.

09:42.880 --> 09:45.200
Finn! Hold the phone. Come here.

09:46.160 --> 09:48.040
-Take the odds.
-Yeah, sure.

09:51.600 --> 09:54.320
(CHATTERING)

09:59.560 --> 10:00.800
Polly.

10:01.680 --> 10:03.360
Did he say who did it?

10:03.440 --> 10:05.360
He's gone to the Black Lion.

10:06.240 --> 10:07.520
On his own?

10:08.000 --> 10:10.360
Tommy does everything on his own.

10:10.600 --> 10:13.080
-Should I go to the Black Lion?
-What?

10:13.160 --> 10:15.640
-Should I go there and see him?
-No.

10:16.480 --> 10:18.360
Where the fuck is Arthur?

10:18.440 --> 10:21.160
Protecting the Garrison's
whisky from the police.

10:21.760 --> 10:23.480
For fuck's sake!

10:27.720 --> 10:32.840
Polly, it feels a little bit to me
like things are getting out of hand.

10:34.040 --> 10:35.400
So get 'em in hand.

10:37.280 --> 10:39.360
Do you know what Ada said to me
this morning?

10:42.280 --> 10:47.120
She said we all look like we work
in a factory under the ground.

10:48.480 --> 10:50.440
She said we look like ghosts.

10:51.560 --> 10:52.840
She'll be back.

10:53.600 --> 10:54.760
When?

10:55.320 --> 10:56.720
When she needs us.

10:58.360 --> 11:02.400
And anyway, who the fuck
would blow up our pub?

11:02.600 --> 11:05.160
-Six.
-Six what?

11:05.360 --> 11:07.600
Six questions since
you walked through the door.

11:11.080 --> 11:14.240
Soon you're going to have to start
being the man with the answers.

11:16.320 --> 11:17.360
Why?

11:19.160 --> 11:20.440
Seven.

11:22.280 --> 11:25.520
Because when London happens,
you'll have to hold up your end

11:26.480 --> 11:28.400
or we'll find somebody else who can.

11:44.240 --> 11:46.680
-(DOOR CLOSES)
-Thomas Shelby.

11:48.800 --> 11:50.240
You blew up my pub.

11:51.760 --> 11:54.080
Anger defeats fear, good.

11:55.120 --> 11:56.760
You blew up my pub.

11:58.760 --> 12:01.240
Tommy has a reputation to uphold.

12:01.600 --> 12:04.400
A reputation for not being
scared of anything.

12:04.680 --> 12:08.960
In all the world, violent men
are the easiest to deal with.

12:11.640 --> 12:14.560
So tell me, which brand
of rebel are you, eh?

12:15.840 --> 12:17.560
I read somewhere that you Paddies

12:17.640 --> 12:19.640
started fighting
amongst yourselves, now.

12:21.240 --> 12:25.520
The King offers you a peace treaty
and you start a war about it.

12:26.080 --> 12:28.640
That's funny, don't you think?

12:29.240 --> 12:30.960
A war about peace.

12:35.480 --> 12:37.920
So are you for the treaty
or against the treaty?

12:38.080 --> 12:40.160
Forgive me, I get confused.

12:47.440 --> 12:50.760
You are one decision away
from death, Mr Shelby.

12:51.640 --> 12:53.680
So stop fucking smiling.

12:57.080 --> 12:59.120
Your name is Irene O'Donnell.

12:59.440 --> 13:02.720
You have a son at the
Cherry wood Road School in Harborne.

13:02.800 --> 13:05.880
He has irons on his legs,
his name is Sean,

13:05.960 --> 13:09.760
he comes last
in every race, poor boy.

13:11.160 --> 13:13.320
Poor boy if the race was important.

13:14.080 --> 13:17.280
Do you know what I mean,
Irene O'Donnell?

13:17.360 --> 13:19.320
There are other ways of
carrying out this mission.

13:19.400 --> 13:22.680
Please allow me to put a bullet
in this scum tinker's head.

13:29.520 --> 13:30.680
No.

13:32.040 --> 13:34.320
He researches his enemies,

13:34.720 --> 13:36.520
that's why he's been chosen.

13:38.240 --> 13:39.640
I am chosen?

13:42.120 --> 13:43.280
I'm chosen.

13:45.360 --> 13:47.200
Can the chosen one smoke?

14:01.920 --> 14:05.920
A vacancy has appeared
and you're going to fill it.

14:09.280 --> 14:10.680
Chosen by whom?

14:12.280 --> 14:14.320
By an informed consensus.

14:16.160 --> 14:17.680
I have things to do.

14:19.440 --> 14:21.640
So perhaps you could tell
the chosen one

14:22.000 --> 14:24.080
what he's been chosen for.

14:25.840 --> 14:27.680
From now on, Mr Shelby,

14:28.000 --> 14:32.320
you shut your fucking gypsy mouth
and listen to your instructions.

15:01.120 --> 15:02.600
Fuck!

15:16.720 --> 15:19.160
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

16:07.640 --> 16:10.640
-(MEN SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)
-(METAL CLANGING)

16:15.240 --> 16:17.680
I need the area round
the co-operative stables

16:17.760 --> 16:20.880
clear of coppers between
midnight and 4:00 tonight.

16:21.360 --> 16:23.240
Right. Could I ask why?

16:26.400 --> 16:30.640
Well, whatever it is you're
going to do, don't start any fires.

16:30.720 --> 16:33.080
The firemen go out
on strike at midnight.

16:33.840 --> 16:35.800
That's all. You can go.

16:41.240 --> 16:44.280
I've got some information
you might be interested in.

16:45.000 --> 16:46.240
No charge.

16:47.480 --> 16:50.040
There's an old friend of ours
coming back to the city.

16:50.120 --> 16:53.440
He's, uh, just passing through, he says.

16:54.320 --> 16:55.600
Very grand these days.

16:55.680 --> 16:58.240
He's head of some
secret department,

16:58.840 --> 17:00.240
the Irish Desk.

17:01.560 --> 17:05.760
So I doubt he'll be bothering
with the likes of us, eh?

17:07.720 --> 17:09.400
I'll say good night, Tom.

17:16.360 --> 17:17.400
(METAL BANGING)

17:17.480 --> 17:20.160
MAN: I demand to speak
to a representative!

17:22.760 --> 17:25.640
(YELLING) A representative of
His Majesty the King!

17:26.160 --> 17:28.880
(SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

17:30.320 --> 17:32.320
Father! Father!

17:32.400 --> 17:35.440
It was the Ulsterman,
the man with the wolf head!

17:35.520 --> 17:37.040
Get the fuck off me!

17:37.120 --> 17:39.960
You must reconcile yourself
with the fate that awaits.

17:40.040 --> 17:43.360
I demand to speak to a representative
of His Majesty the King!

17:43.440 --> 17:44.720
Make your peace with God.

17:44.800 --> 17:47.840
A representative of
His Majesty the King!

17:48.000 --> 17:49.480
-Father.
-Come on.

17:49.560 --> 17:51.520
MAN: Now, wait!
Where are you going?

17:52.520 --> 17:53.560
(LOCKING DOOR)

17:53.640 --> 17:56.400
Does someone here have
business with the King?

17:57.080 --> 17:58.600
Major Campbell.

17:58.680 --> 18:00.960
-(SHOUTING CONTINUES)
-About time.

18:02.520 --> 18:05.560
I am a very busy man, Governor.

18:05.760 --> 18:07.120
In seven and a half minutes,

18:07.200 --> 18:09.880
the man in that cell
is due to be hanged for murder.

18:11.000 --> 18:13.800
The murder of an Irish activist
in Whitechapel.

18:13.880 --> 18:16.560
Does the case ring any bells,
Major Campbell?

18:17.840 --> 18:19.120
No, Governor,

18:19.640 --> 18:21.160
I hear no bells.

18:23.120 --> 18:24.480
Since yesterday morning,

18:24.560 --> 18:26.560
he's been claiming that the murder
was ordered

18:26.640 --> 18:28.720
by the British
Secret Intelligence Service.

18:28.800 --> 18:31.800
(SCOFFS) It's a little late
to be coming up with nonsense like that,

18:31.880 --> 18:33.080
don't you think?

18:33.160 --> 18:35.000
He was told if he kept
his mouth shut

18:35.080 --> 18:37.000
there would be a last-minute pardon,

18:37.360 --> 18:39.360
which has not materialised.

18:40.720 --> 18:42.400
Forgive me, Governor,

18:43.200 --> 18:45.720
but what business is this of mine?

18:47.480 --> 18:49.000
He says the man who hired him

18:49.080 --> 18:51.520
was an Intelligence Service
Chief of Staff,

18:52.480 --> 18:53.880
an Ulsterman.

18:54.480 --> 18:56.920
Carries a cane
with a wolf-head handle,

18:57.000 --> 18:59.000
a bullet wound in his right leg.

18:59.760 --> 19:00.920
No.

19:03.000 --> 19:05.160
Still no bells. Governor,

19:06.960 --> 19:10.080
you have a very clear remit.

19:10.480 --> 19:14.240
Part of that remit is
to oversee the smooth completion

19:14.520 --> 19:17.640
of executions
sanctioned by the Crown.

19:18.000 --> 19:22.680
And in the next four minutes it is
your duty to escort that man

19:23.240 --> 19:24.960
to the gates of hell.

19:25.720 --> 19:27.000
Is that clear?

19:29.920 --> 19:33.400
And if you should ever have
the desire

19:33.480 --> 19:36.000
to discuss this matter
with anyone else

19:37.440 --> 19:40.040
I know where you live.

19:43.400 --> 19:45.200
(PANICKED BREATHING)

19:54.240 --> 19:57.760
Arthur, Tommy's
called a family meeting.

19:59.400 --> 20:00.440
Arthur!

20:00.520 --> 20:02.840
He just beat the shit out of
an apprentice.

20:02.920 --> 20:05.400
I had to take half the kid away
in buckets.

20:13.640 --> 20:14.840
Arthur.

20:17.160 --> 20:19.080
(HEAVY BREATHING)

20:19.720 --> 20:21.160
2,000.

20:41.160 --> 20:42.480
Come on.

20:51.080 --> 20:52.480
Sit down, Finn.

21:05.280 --> 21:08.200
-Where the bloody hell is Tommy?
-He's on his way.

21:09.800 --> 21:12.240
All right then,
while we're waiting patiently...

21:14.880 --> 21:16.880
Whisky.
(STRAINS)

21:17.440 --> 21:19.720
Left over from the explosion.

21:21.680 --> 21:23.160
It's good stuff, as well.

21:37.680 --> 21:38.920
Right.

21:39.640 --> 21:41.160
Before Tommy gets here,

21:42.200 --> 21:44.160
I think there's a few things
we need to get straight

21:44.240 --> 21:45.640
between the rest of us.

21:45.720 --> 21:46.840
You think?

21:48.080 --> 21:49.200
Yeah.

21:50.400 --> 21:52.320
Yeah, I do. I want to know...

21:54.040 --> 21:56.920
When did we all take a vote
on this expansion south?

22:01.440 --> 22:03.400
You have anything to say,

22:03.800 --> 22:05.280
you wait for Thomas.

22:05.360 --> 22:06.680
Polly's fucking right.

22:06.760 --> 22:08.320
I see all the books.

22:09.360 --> 22:12.240
Legal and off track.

22:13.680 --> 22:15.400
Sort of stuff you don't see.

22:17.360 --> 22:18.880
And in the past year

22:19.840 --> 22:21.480
the Shelby Company Limited

22:21.560 --> 22:25.840
has been making £150

22:26.720 --> 22:28.000
a day.

22:30.040 --> 22:31.880
Right? A fucking day!

22:31.960 --> 22:33.400
Sometimes more.

22:33.920 --> 22:35.720
So what I want to know

22:37.200 --> 22:40.240
is why are we changing things?

22:40.520 --> 22:43.040
Polly, look what's happened already.

22:44.200 --> 22:46.040
We haven't even set foot
in London yet

22:46.200 --> 22:47.960
and they've already blown up
our fucking pub.

22:48.040 --> 22:50.400
-Who said anything about cockneys?
-Who else?

22:50.480 --> 22:52.200
Do you know who did it, do you?

22:52.560 --> 22:54.920
-No, she doesn't know who did it.
-(DOOR OPENING)

22:56.280 --> 22:58.640
I'm told only family
are allowed to speak.

22:59.240 --> 23:00.960
Everyone's allowed to speak.

23:01.920 --> 23:05.040
On your feet, Esme,
let's hear what you have to say.

23:06.280 --> 23:07.440
(CLEARING THROAT)

23:08.280 --> 23:10.040
I speak for our household.

23:11.440 --> 23:13.880
-So...
-John, this company is

23:13.960 --> 23:17.280
a modern enterprise and believes in
equal rights for women.

23:17.440 --> 23:18.800
On your feet, Esme.

23:31.600 --> 23:34.160
I'm not a blood member
of this family

23:34.840 --> 23:37.120
but perhaps, indeed,
because I'm not a member

23:37.200 --> 23:39.360
I can see things
in a different light.

23:40.640 --> 23:42.160
So I'll get to my point.

23:42.480 --> 23:43.960
That would be nice.

23:44.200 --> 23:45.320
As my husband said,

23:45.400 --> 23:48.120
Shelby Company Limited
is now very successful.

23:48.200 --> 23:50.080
-(MATCH STRIKES)
-But London...

23:51.280 --> 23:54.000
I have kin in Shepherd's Bush
and Portobello.

23:54.880 --> 23:57.320
It's more like wars
between armies down there.

23:58.080 --> 24:00.760
And the coppers fight
side-by-side with them.

24:01.600 --> 24:04.920
And there are foreigners
of every description

24:06.040 --> 24:08.320
and the use of bombs
is the least of it.

24:10.960 --> 24:12.440
I have a child,

24:13.920 --> 24:16.320
blessed with the Shelby family
good looks.

24:17.720 --> 24:19.800
I want John to see him grow up.

24:21.240 --> 24:25.040
I want us to someday live somewhere
with fresh air and trees

24:25.320 --> 24:27.200
and keep chickens or something.

24:28.600 --> 24:32.360
But London is just smoke
and trouble, Thomas.

24:32.880 --> 24:34.040
Thomas?

24:37.680 --> 24:39.200
That's all I have to say.

24:41.320 --> 24:45.520
That was a lot of words,
a lot of words.

24:48.360 --> 24:50.480
Wash them down with a nice drink.

24:51.160 --> 24:52.480
Thank you, Esme.

24:55.320 --> 24:58.120
Firstly, the bang in the pub
had nothing to do with London.

24:58.200 --> 24:59.480
Understood?

24:59.720 --> 25:01.720
The bang is something
I'm dealing with on my own.

25:01.800 --> 25:05.680
Secondly, we've nothing to fear
from the proposed business expansion

25:05.760 --> 25:07.560
so long as we stick together.

25:08.880 --> 25:10.080
And after the first few weeks,

25:10.160 --> 25:12.400
nine tenths of what we do in London
will be legal.

25:13.120 --> 25:16.520
The other tenth is in good hands.
Isn't that right, Arthur?

25:16.760 --> 25:17.960
That's right.

25:19.800 --> 25:22.200
Now, some of you in this room
have expressed your reservations.

25:22.280 --> 25:23.480
Fair enough.

25:23.800 --> 25:26.920
Any of you who want no part
in the future of this company,

25:27.160 --> 25:28.560
walk out the door...

25:31.040 --> 25:32.040
(SNIFFS)

25:32.720 --> 25:34.040
Right now.

25:35.640 --> 25:37.400
Go raise your chickens.

25:39.680 --> 25:41.680
For those of you with ambition

25:42.560 --> 25:44.640
the expansion process
begins tomorrow.

25:50.000 --> 25:51.000
(CLEARS THROAT)

25:58.480 --> 25:59.920
Tomorrow?

26:00.400 --> 26:03.080
I'm company treasurer,
you should speak to me first.

26:04.880 --> 26:08.120
It's New market tomorrow,
third busiest day of the year.

26:08.200 --> 26:09.760
We have 18 staff.

26:09.840 --> 26:12.160
Who you trust with 200 quid takings?

26:12.240 --> 26:14.400
Oh, I changed the combination.

26:17.760 --> 26:21.680
-(SIGHS)
-So what's going on, Thomas?

26:22.520 --> 26:24.640
Who'd you meet at the Black Lion?

26:26.520 --> 26:28.640
Give me the combination, Polly.

26:30.560 --> 26:32.080
(PENCIL SCRIBBLING)

26:33.200 --> 26:34.200
(BANGS TABLE)

26:35.080 --> 26:38.080
Polly, give me the combination.

26:44.640 --> 26:47.040
What happened to the pub
is Irish business.

26:47.360 --> 26:49.480
We're in a situation where,
for everyone's safety,

26:49.560 --> 26:52.440
it's best if some things
remain undisclosed.

26:53.320 --> 26:54.640
So why tomorrow?

26:57.600 --> 26:59.680
Like you say,
tomorrow's New market.

26:59.760 --> 27:01.920
All the London bosses
will be at the races.

27:02.200 --> 27:04.280
What say you just roll up
and take the city?

27:04.680 --> 27:08.000
No, we take the opportunity
to show our hand.

27:10.840 --> 27:12.800
The Italian gangs
and the Jewish gangs

27:12.880 --> 27:14.800
have been at war in London
for six months.

27:14.880 --> 27:16.000
It's not our war.

27:16.080 --> 27:18.400
The Jews have been having
the worst of it. They need allies.

27:18.480 --> 27:20.840
-Yeah, but we don't.
-We need a foothold

27:20.920 --> 27:23.000
at the southern end
of the Grand Union.

27:23.080 --> 27:25.240
The Jews control Camden Town.

27:29.880 --> 27:31.560
(DEEP BREATH)

27:33.400 --> 27:34.880
Your mother said,

27:35.440 --> 27:37.400
"It's his cleverness
that'll kill him."

27:39.320 --> 27:41.200
No-one gets killed, Polly.

27:41.680 --> 27:45.160
We go down tomorrow when it's quiet
and we leave our message.

27:45.240 --> 27:48.440
If Alfie Solomon
and his Camden boys come to us,

27:48.520 --> 27:50.920
we'll negotiate the use
of a secure bonded warehouse

27:51.000 --> 27:53.720
and then our legal activities
in London can begin.

27:53.800 --> 27:57.880
Now please, open the fucking safe.

28:04.200 --> 28:07.480
Do you know, it was a fine speech
you made in there,

28:08.280 --> 28:11.680
about this company believing
in equal rights for women.

28:12.880 --> 28:14.600
But when it comes to it,

28:14.800 --> 28:16.800
you don't listen to a word we say.

28:18.240 --> 28:20.000
Maybe you don't trust us.

28:22.840 --> 28:24.600
She was one woman, Thomas.

28:31.600 --> 28:33.840
Well, maybe it's time
you forgot about her.

28:33.920 --> 28:35.400
Forgot about who?

28:35.480 --> 28:37.120
(SIGHS)

28:38.440 --> 28:40.080
(UNLOCKING THE SAFE)

28:49.520 --> 28:51.960
You and the boys,
go and get yourselves killed.

28:58.240 --> 28:59.840
(COINS RATTLING)

29:02.040 --> 29:04.240
(DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES)

29:05.080 --> 29:07.160
(GRUNTING)

29:28.400 --> 29:30.160
(EXHALES HEAVILY)

29:43.600 --> 29:45.440
Are you going to London now?

29:48.120 --> 29:51.400
No, there's something
I have to do first.

29:52.200 --> 29:54.920
Oh, I've got a typewriter like that.

29:55.640 --> 29:57.240
I got it out of a catalogue.

29:57.840 --> 30:00.280
I'm doing a correspondence course.

30:03.440 --> 30:05.240
I'm learning to do it
with my eyes shut.

30:05.320 --> 30:06.960
It's a test you have to do.

30:14.520 --> 30:16.600
Will you come back before you go?

30:21.200 --> 30:22.400
No.

30:39.320 --> 30:42.320
I wish, just once,
you wouldn't pay me,

30:42.880 --> 30:44.680
as if we were ordinary people.

30:45.080 --> 30:46.160
Yeah.

30:46.840 --> 30:49.600
(DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES)

31:50.000 --> 31:51.520
Let's begin.

31:52.160 --> 31:53.800
Hands on the table.

32:01.320 --> 32:03.720
Tonight we have two
new pilgrims joining us.

32:03.800 --> 32:05.960
So, let's welcome them.

32:11.440 --> 32:12.800
Starting with you.

32:13.520 --> 32:15.720
Who is it that
you're seeking to reach?

32:16.640 --> 32:18.000
My husband.

32:18.800 --> 32:21.760
He was taken six months ago
by the influenza.

32:22.800 --> 32:25.440
I tried to reach him through
Mrs Breach at Sparkhill

32:25.520 --> 32:28.360
but she kept getting
his middle name wrong.

32:28.640 --> 32:31.520
MEDIUM: Don't talk about Mrs Breach
in this house.

32:32.920 --> 32:35.640
She's an unsanctified charlatan.

32:40.600 --> 32:41.840
And you?

32:44.240 --> 32:45.720
Who do you seek?

32:47.600 --> 32:49.720
Well, truth...

32:49.800 --> 32:52.760
Sorry, truth is,
I'm not even sure she's dead.

32:52.840 --> 32:54.840
So I came here to find out.

32:59.560 --> 33:00.800
Er...

33:02.920 --> 33:05.000
You see, my son and my daughter

33:05.320 --> 33:08.000
were taken from me
when they were very small.

33:08.360 --> 33:10.040
Taken by the parish authorities

33:10.120 --> 33:12.040
and I never knew
what happened to them.

33:13.120 --> 33:16.120
But lately...

33:18.000 --> 33:19.480
I've had a feeling.

33:21.640 --> 33:23.000
Like, a feeling...

33:27.200 --> 33:29.040
I can't put it into words.

33:30.680 --> 33:33.200
And I keep having a dream.

33:36.600 --> 33:39.400
I see a pretty girl,

33:40.480 --> 33:42.120
about 18-years-old.

33:43.840 --> 33:46.440
She's standing
across the street

33:48.240 --> 33:52.160
and she tells me
she's passed over.

33:52.800 --> 33:56.800
Now, my daughter
would have been 18 this year.

33:57.520 --> 33:59.840
On May 15th.

34:05.280 --> 34:09.160
And this girl has dark eyes
like mine.

34:13.640 --> 34:17.480
And she shouts and shouts.

34:19.080 --> 34:23.200
And she tells me
she wants to talk to me

34:23.640 --> 34:25.200
because I'm her mother.

34:30.000 --> 34:33.920
Now, I don't even know
what name they gave her

34:34.400 --> 34:36.360
after they stole her from me.

34:39.600 --> 34:41.960
But if she does want
to say goodbye,

34:43.000 --> 34:44.920
I thought this would be the place.

34:48.960 --> 34:50.960
You're wearing the Black Madonna.

34:51.880 --> 34:53.120
You're gypsy?

34:54.320 --> 34:57.120
The part of me that dreams is gypsy.

35:01.480 --> 35:04.040
(SPEAKING ROMANI)

35:12.000 --> 35:14.080
My maiden name is Shelby.

35:23.760 --> 35:24.880
So,

35:26.760 --> 35:28.720
perhaps you could do me first.

35:35.320 --> 35:36.680
No!

35:39.960 --> 35:41.480
(YELLS)

35:42.240 --> 35:43.680
No!

35:45.280 --> 35:46.920
(SCREAMING)
No!

35:53.600 --> 35:55.640
(CRYING)

35:58.480 --> 36:00.240
(WHIMPERING) No...

36:02.240 --> 36:04.280
(CLANKING)

37:55.360 --> 37:56.880
Eamonn Duggan?

38:20.640 --> 38:22.440
ARTHUR: All right, Tommy's here.

38:22.760 --> 38:24.320
JOHN: Hang on!

38:30.280 --> 38:31.520
John!

38:31.600 --> 38:32.920
I'm coming!

38:41.320 --> 38:44.000
7 o'clock, 12 o'clock,

38:44.080 --> 38:45.800
10 if I'm still sober.

38:46.400 --> 38:48.240
I got it from the doctor.

38:49.440 --> 38:51.520
Keeps me nice and calm.

38:53.800 --> 38:55.640
Same thing they gave us
in the trenches

38:55.720 --> 38:57.480
to stop us fucking wanking.

38:57.560 --> 38:59.160
Polly said it's good for me temper.

38:59.240 --> 39:01.200
-It slows me down, Tom.
-Arthur,

39:01.560 --> 39:04.080
there are some things
Polly doesn't understand.

39:04.160 --> 39:08.000
-I need you fast. Not slow, eh?
-(DOOR OPENS)

39:08.200 --> 39:09.800
JOHN: She wouldn't let go
of my fucking leg.

39:09.880 --> 39:11.480
I bet that's not all
she wouldn't let go of.

39:11.560 --> 39:15.760
Right. You know she's against this, Tom.
She's got opinions.

39:15.840 --> 39:17.520
Nothing wrong with opinions, John.
Come on.

39:17.600 --> 39:19.280
-Get in the fucking car!
-Shut up.

39:19.360 --> 39:21.640
(ENGINE STARTING)

39:24.280 --> 39:25.600
(SHOUTS) Right!

39:25.680 --> 39:28.600
The Peaky Blinders are going
on fucking holiday!

39:28.680 --> 39:30.960
Sit down, you mad bastard.
(LAUGHING)

39:36.760 --> 39:38.320
(DOOR CLOSES)

39:55.640 --> 39:57.960
You're against this
the same as me, aren't you?

40:00.520 --> 40:02.960
Look out for anyone putting
big money on Divine Star

40:03.040 --> 40:05.000
in the 3:30 at New market.

40:05.840 --> 40:07.200
She's one of ours.

40:08.400 --> 40:11.240
Anything over a pound, tell me.

40:17.880 --> 40:18.920
Polly,

40:20.240 --> 40:22.440
I don't wish to pry
into your business,

40:23.120 --> 40:24.760
but you should know something.

40:26.080 --> 40:28.040
That woman is a trickster.

40:28.360 --> 40:29.720
What woman?

40:30.440 --> 40:32.880
Her sister was in
the wash house early,

40:33.560 --> 40:36.000
boasting there'd been
a Shelby at the table.

40:40.040 --> 40:41.160
What woman?

40:42.160 --> 40:43.960
Gypsies talk to each other.

40:46.000 --> 40:47.720
What woman?

40:50.120 --> 40:52.840
You went to see Mrs Price
in the Patch last night.

40:58.200 --> 40:59.560
I'm sorry...

41:00.440 --> 41:01.880
So what do you know?

41:02.120 --> 41:03.880
I know they push the glass.

41:04.280 --> 41:06.200
The man, it's her cousin.
He pushes the glass.

41:06.280 --> 41:07.440
It's a trick.

41:07.920 --> 41:10.040
They tell you what
you already believe.

41:12.080 --> 41:14.920
She set up after the war
because of all the widows.

41:15.640 --> 41:19.120
Polly, I just thought
you should know.

41:19.200 --> 41:21.040
And in this fucking wash house,

41:21.120 --> 41:22.960
did they tell you why I went there?

41:29.520 --> 41:32.880
You tell a soul in this family,

41:33.720 --> 41:37.200
and I swear I will cut you.

41:39.160 --> 41:43.320
I don't need a knife to stop me
telling secrets given in confidence.

41:44.600 --> 41:46.480
It is a matter of hon our.

42:04.720 --> 42:06.240
(DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES)

42:07.440 --> 42:09.120
ARTHUR: Look at this! Look.

42:09.480 --> 42:10.840
-I love it.
-(URINATING)

42:11.040 --> 42:13.440
Your Esme was right
about one thing,

42:13.520 --> 42:15.800
you can't beat the countryside.

42:16.960 --> 42:20.560
You know, I think I want
to live in the country one day

42:21.120 --> 42:22.600
and keep chickens.

42:23.160 --> 42:25.320
Yeah, we'll see you
in London, Arthur.

42:30.000 --> 42:32.480
-Oh, for fuck's sake!
-Take this.

42:36.080 --> 42:37.480
We need to bury him.

42:37.560 --> 42:39.160
JOHN: Who the fuck is that?

42:39.560 --> 42:40.880
It's Irish business.

42:40.960 --> 42:43.200
I thought it best
if I deal with it on my own.

42:43.760 --> 42:46.280
Come on, we did a thousand
of these in France.

42:46.360 --> 42:47.720
John, grab his head.

42:48.080 --> 42:50.040
So, we're not really
going to London?

42:50.800 --> 42:52.280
Once we bury him,

42:52.800 --> 42:54.480
then the holiday begins.

43:01.440 --> 43:03.760
(GIGGLING)

43:04.240 --> 43:06.360
(CAR HORN HONKS)

43:20.280 --> 43:21.720
Much obliged.

43:24.280 --> 43:26.800
(BAND PLAYING)

43:27.600 --> 43:29.560
(LAUGHING)

43:30.960 --> 43:33.320
It's a fucking freak show.

43:33.720 --> 43:35.600
(WOMEN PANTING)

43:42.400 --> 43:44.360
(LOUD JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING)

43:52.920 --> 43:55.440
What the fuck is that racket?

43:55.520 --> 43:57.800
This is what they call music
these days, brother.

43:57.880 --> 43:59.040
Music?

44:03.200 --> 44:04.400
(SNIFFING)

44:16.320 --> 44:17.400
Oi!

44:17.480 --> 44:19.920
Oi! Put it away.

44:20.000 --> 44:21.360
Fuck off!

44:26.280 --> 44:28.480
Fucking look at this spot, eh?

44:28.920 --> 44:30.560
It's all right, isn't it?

44:35.000 --> 44:37.480
Irish whiskey, a bottle.

44:38.160 --> 44:39.800
And hurry up!

44:43.960 --> 44:45.520
Fucking hell,

44:45.600 --> 44:47.600
I recognise a few of these lads.

44:49.880 --> 44:51.760
That's Sabini's cousin, over there.

44:52.640 --> 44:55.200
TOMMY: That's right, Arthur,
it's Sabini's club.

44:55.400 --> 44:58.720
Jesus Christ,
everybody in here's a fucking face.

44:58.800 --> 45:02.800
Just the lieutenants, John.
No sign of the officers.

45:04.360 --> 45:06.040
Right, let's line them up.

45:07.880 --> 45:09.080
Holiday!

45:11.400 --> 45:13.520
Gentlemen, there's been a mistake.

45:13.600 --> 45:15.560
I'm afraid you're going to
have to leave.

45:16.720 --> 45:18.640
We just bought a fucking bottle.

45:18.720 --> 45:22.080
Some of the men here recognise you
from the racetracks in the north.

45:22.200 --> 45:24.480
Yeah, we get that a lot.

45:24.560 --> 45:27.600
They say you have no business
coming south of the line

45:27.680 --> 45:29.560
without prior agreement.

45:29.800 --> 45:32.000
And what line would that be,
my friend?

45:33.200 --> 45:35.640
They say this is provocation.

45:37.280 --> 45:40.440
Right, well, you tell them
we're on holiday.

45:42.120 --> 45:43.840
You're breaking the rules.

45:45.680 --> 45:48.800
They say you are
the Peaky Blinders...

45:49.120 --> 45:50.520
(MAN SHOUTS) Peaky scum!

45:54.160 --> 45:57.160
(BAND CONTINUES PLAYING)

45:58.840 --> 46:01.280
-(GLASS SHATTERING)
-(MEN GRUNTING)

46:11.560 --> 46:15.680
(LAUGHING)
Who the fuck's next?

46:19.120 --> 46:20.440
Come here!

46:21.760 --> 46:24.080
(GRUNTING)

46:26.360 --> 46:27.880
(PEOPLE SHRIEK)

46:28.920 --> 46:30.800
Put some ice on 'em!

46:34.880 --> 46:36.280
Get out.

46:39.800 --> 46:41.080
Yeah?

46:43.520 --> 46:44.840
Yeah?

46:45.200 --> 46:46.440
Are you going to use that?

46:51.240 --> 46:52.480
Didn't think so.

47:10.080 --> 47:13.400
We came here
not to make enemies.

47:15.440 --> 47:16.560
No.

47:17.920 --> 47:20.560
We came here to make new friends!

47:20.640 --> 47:21.640
-(THUD)
-(GRUNT)

47:24.960 --> 47:27.160
Those of you who are last

47:27.720 --> 47:29.800
will soon be first.

47:33.560 --> 47:37.640
And those of you who are downtrodden
will rise up.

47:39.680 --> 47:40.800
Yup.

47:42.320 --> 47:44.200
You know where to find us.

47:52.920 --> 47:54.720
ARTHUR: I think I've lost a tooth.

47:55.200 --> 47:57.640
I'll have none left at this rate!
(SPITS)

47:57.800 --> 47:59.600
Some fucking holiday this is.

47:59.760 --> 48:02.920
Yeah? You all right without
your fucking medicine, Arthur?

48:03.000 --> 48:05.480
-Here, this'll fix you.
-Give me that!

48:05.560 --> 48:07.840
-You, John boy, eh? How are you?
-(YELLS)

48:07.920 --> 48:10.480
-Or should I ask your fucking wife?
-Oh, give over!

48:10.560 --> 48:12.080
No more talk of chickens,
do you hear me?

48:12.160 --> 48:13.840
-(LAUGHING)
-Fuck the chickens.

48:13.920 --> 48:15.640
I've 50 quid in me pocket.

48:15.720 --> 48:17.080
Let's paint the town, eh?

48:17.160 --> 48:18.960
(JOHN CHEERS)

48:19.360 --> 48:21.520
-(KNOCK ON DOOR)
-MAN: Come.

48:25.160 --> 48:27.680
-Oh, dear God!
-Good Lord, I assumed

48:27.760 --> 48:29.520
it was Betty with tea.

48:30.320 --> 48:33.640
Forgive me, sir, but your secretary
was not at the desk.

48:33.720 --> 48:36.960
No, because she takes lunch,
like normal people.

48:37.440 --> 48:38.480
And you can turn around,

48:38.560 --> 48:41.200
this lady is
a professional life model.

48:41.280 --> 48:42.880
She does this for a living.

48:44.400 --> 48:47.040
I... I'm more than happy
to come back later, sir.

48:47.120 --> 48:50.120
No, no, no. Later on
I'm in the House. Just, erm,

48:51.960 --> 48:54.480
keep your back turned,
if you must.

48:54.560 --> 48:55.920
Yes, sir.

48:59.200 --> 49:03.880
I would guess you haven't been
exposed to Bohemian society, Major?

49:05.000 --> 49:08.280
Well, I... I...
I play cards on occasion.

49:08.360 --> 49:12.800
You're a stranger to cocaine and
exotic dancing, too, I would imagine.

49:13.160 --> 49:17.320
I find the more obvious vices
the easiest to resist.

49:17.400 --> 49:22.240
It's the sneaky little obscure ones
that bring you to your knees, yes?

49:22.920 --> 49:26.760
So what business is so urgent
it trumps lunch?

49:27.000 --> 49:29.040
Well, sir, our man in Birmingham

49:29.120 --> 49:31.560
has passed his first test
with flying colours.

49:31.640 --> 49:33.440
Oh, I'm horrible at faces.

49:33.520 --> 49:36.520
So I think we can begin to
prepare him for...

49:37.520 --> 49:38.840
The bigger task.

49:39.000 --> 49:41.320
Expressions elude me,
I think too much.

49:41.400 --> 49:42.560
Sir?

49:42.880 --> 49:45.800
I need your authority

49:45.880 --> 49:48.680
to proceed with all urgency

49:49.200 --> 49:52.520
in preparing the new man
for the bigger task.

49:52.640 --> 49:55.200
You're talking about
your bookmaker.

49:55.640 --> 49:56.680
Yes, sir.

49:56.760 --> 50:00.040
You have a history with this man.
Why did you choose him?

50:01.480 --> 50:05.360
Well, to apply pressure on a man
for this type of work

50:05.440 --> 50:07.040
you have to know his weaknesses

50:07.120 --> 50:10.720
and I know this man's
weaknesses intimately.

50:10.800 --> 50:13.000
And after "mission accomplished",

50:13.080 --> 50:15.560
do we trust him
to keep his mouth shut?

50:16.280 --> 50:18.000
Absolutely not, sir.

50:19.360 --> 50:21.760
So when he's served his purpose,

50:21.920 --> 50:23.680
he will be consigned to history

50:23.760 --> 50:25.960
in exactly the same way
as his predecessor.

50:26.040 --> 50:28.360
You mean at the end of a rope?

50:29.640 --> 50:32.680
Well, the end of the rope has
been this man's destiny

50:33.720 --> 50:35.680
since the night he was born.

51:01.880 --> 51:03.440
(DOOR OPENS)

51:04.520 --> 51:05.920
You're early.

51:07.280 --> 51:08.880
Shut your eyes, Lizzie.

51:09.800 --> 51:10.800
What?

51:10.880 --> 51:13.880
Shut your eyes.
Go on, shut your eyes.

51:15.600 --> 51:18.080
Good. Now, come with me.

51:18.160 --> 51:19.680
No, shut your eyes!

51:20.080 --> 51:21.520
-(CHUCKLES)
-This way.

51:21.600 --> 51:23.280
What are you doing, Tom?

51:23.360 --> 51:25.400
You've got to sit down
here. Right.

51:26.480 --> 51:30.520
-(CLEARS THROAT)
-Sit down. Now, okay...

51:31.040 --> 51:32.800
-Type this.
-Why?

51:32.880 --> 51:34.320
Lizzie, type this.

51:34.840 --> 51:37.000
"If wi..."
Put your cigarette out.

51:37.960 --> 51:40.080
Right. "If winter comes...

51:40.400 --> 51:44.560
-(STARTS TYPING)
-"...then can spring be far behind?"

51:44.640 --> 51:48.000
(CHUCKLING) Why?
Did you say spring?

51:48.080 --> 51:49.920
Lizzie, what comes after winter?

51:53.680 --> 51:54.960
Let's see.

51:55.720 --> 51:57.560
That's a question.
Where's the question mark?

51:57.640 --> 51:58.960
Put in the question mark.

52:00.000 --> 52:01.760
Now type this.

52:01.840 --> 52:05.280
"Wanted, secretary
for expanding business."

52:05.360 --> 52:06.640
Slow down!

52:06.720 --> 52:09.640
"Must be able to take dictation
and touch type.

52:10.640 --> 52:12.200
"Five days a week.

52:12.280 --> 52:16.120
"Uh, eight pounds
and four shillings a month.

52:16.200 --> 52:18.440
"Must be able to start immediately."

52:19.800 --> 52:21.080
Are you serious?

52:24.720 --> 52:26.720
Things are starting
to happen, Lizzie.

52:29.120 --> 52:31.920
I need someone who can
look the other way sometimes.

52:39.200 --> 52:41.440
And you can stop
the other work too, Lizzie.

52:42.840 --> 52:45.240
All of it this time.

52:47.200 --> 52:48.520
No exceptions.

52:54.800 --> 52:57.720
Eight o'clock, Monday morning,
the upstairs office.

52:57.800 --> 52:58.880
Don't be late.

53:09.160 --> 53:10.400
(DOOR OPENS)

53:11.840 --> 53:13.520
New market was profitable.

53:14.320 --> 53:16.680
Arthur told me
how you left your message.

53:17.840 --> 53:20.320
And when I asked him
where his medicine was,

53:20.400 --> 53:21.600
he said you poured it away.

53:21.680 --> 53:24.160
All I poured away was opium
and bromide.

53:25.080 --> 53:27.160
Oh, that's how it works
in London, isn't it?

53:27.240 --> 53:29.880
Every boss has to have
a mad dog at his side.

53:29.960 --> 53:33.240
Yeah, somebody who can't be
predicted, somebody mad in the head.

53:33.320 --> 53:35.360
But Thomas Shelby
uses his own brother.

53:35.440 --> 53:38.480
-Stop fucking fighting me!
-Somebody has to.

53:39.760 --> 53:41.320
That arrived an hour ago.

53:41.400 --> 53:44.000
There's no name on it
but it comes from Camden Town.

53:44.920 --> 53:46.240
I was going to burn it.

53:46.320 --> 53:47.680
I should have.

53:47.800 --> 53:50.960
Well done, Tommy,
you've picked a side.

53:51.280 --> 53:53.360
Now you're at war with Sabini.

54:33.000 --> 54:35.440
Ada, are you coming for a drink?

54:35.520 --> 54:38.160
No, the woman upstairs
is looking after Karl.

54:38.240 --> 54:39.960
She goes mad if I'm late!

55:11.440 --> 55:13.560
-Ada Shelby?
-No.

55:15.840 --> 55:18.080
(GRUNTING)

55:22.160 --> 55:23.680
Your brother broke the rules.

55:23.760 --> 55:25.040
I don't have a fucking brother.

55:25.120 --> 55:27.600
Me and my friends here need
a bit of female company.

55:27.680 --> 55:29.280
-Let's go for a drive.
-No!

55:29.480 --> 55:31.320
-Hold her steady, boys.
-Don't! Get off!

55:37.880 --> 55:40.200
(YELLS)

55:43.520 --> 55:45.800
-Fucking hold him!
-(TOMMY GRUNTING)

55:51.680 --> 55:53.920
(TOMMY GROANS)

56:14.400 --> 56:18.560
Tommy Shelby,
I missed you at my club.

56:18.960 --> 56:20.960
I was at the races.

56:21.440 --> 56:22.760
Sabini.

56:25.160 --> 56:26.680
Don't say my name.

56:27.680 --> 56:29.160
Jesus!

56:29.560 --> 56:30.760
Franco,

56:31.400 --> 56:33.440
take my name out of his mouth.

56:35.600 --> 56:38.080
(TOMMY GROANS AND GURGLES)

56:43.480 --> 56:45.240
While you're in there,
do a bit of digging for gold.

56:45.320 --> 56:46.520
Pay for the petrol.

56:46.600 --> 56:49.120
(MOANS)

56:52.680 --> 56:54.720
(SPLUTTERS)

56:59.080 --> 57:00.080
(RETCHING)

57:02.280 --> 57:04.160
You see how much I know about you?

57:04.680 --> 57:07.840
I even know what's in
your fucking mouth.

57:08.680 --> 57:10.520
Look at me.
Look at me!

57:11.480 --> 57:12.720
Look at me.

57:14.280 --> 57:16.200
You take up with the Jews.

57:16.280 --> 57:18.760
Yeah, you think that's
what London's all about.

57:18.840 --> 57:21.240
You can just come down,
pick a side.

57:21.320 --> 57:23.440
You fucking clown!

57:24.000 --> 57:25.960
Now your life is over.

57:26.640 --> 57:30.520
My face is the last thing
you'll ever see on earth.

57:30.920 --> 57:32.280
Your mistake.

57:32.360 --> 57:34.640
You remember that
when you get to hell.

57:40.200 --> 57:41.640
Finish him off.

57:43.520 --> 57:46.000
(GUNSHOTS AND SHOUTING)

57:46.480 --> 57:48.920
-(WHISTLES BLOW)
-You! Get back here!

57:52.040 --> 57:54.200
(CAR ENGINE STARTS)

57:54.520 --> 57:56.400
-(FOOTSTEPS DRAW NEAR)
-(METAL BANGING)

58:09.120 --> 58:13.760
CAMPBELL: I suppose we should
see if the bastard's still alive.

58:13.784 --> 58:18.784
http://hiqve.com/
